The paper deals with the problem of network alignment, which is a common problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) when dealing with networked data sources. The paper also discusses the use of human experts to assist in the alignment process, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The paper proposes a novel approach to active network alignment, which involves constructing and solving a bipartite matching problem, which is a common problem in data structures (cs.DS) and databases (cs.DB). Finally, the paper presents experimental results on both synthetic and real-world datasets, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
